Davus is interrupted by the appearance of Geta, who is seen here coming out to look for him, and leaving instructions at home, if Davus should inquire for him after he was gone. When they meet they fall into conversation, in which the whole mystery of the play is laid open: the danger that threatened Geta, by the precipitata behaviour of his master‘s son ; the anxiety of the young man himself, lest, at his father’s return, his Phanium should be torn from him ; and the distress Phaedria was in, that he could not come at the possession of the music- girl.
